defaultQ80 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default 
default 
defaultI welcome members of the public to this sitting of the Select Committee on Foreign Affairs, which is our second oral evidence session of the Committee’s short inquiry into UK policy towards Iran. We have been fortunate because an all-party group has recently been to Iran and the members have agreed to come and speak to us today. Mr Straw, are you officially the leader of the group.
default              
defaultMr Straw:default The unofficial leader.
defaultQ81 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default The 
defaultunofficial
default leader of the group is former Foreign Secretary, Jack Straw. The other members are Mr Ben Wallace of the Conservative party, the right hon. Lord Lamont, former Chancellor of the Exchequer and a member of the Conservative party, and Mr 
defaultCorbyn
default, Labour Member of Parliament. Gentlemen, I welcome you all. We are grateful to you for giving up your time to come and see us.
default              
defaultMr Straw:default Thank you for the invitation, Mr Chairman. Mr Wallace and I are co-chairmen of the all-party group on 
defaultIran
default. Ecumenical we may be in other respects, but we had a happy and comradely trip to 
defaultIran
default.
defaultQ82 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default I am 
defaultpleased
default to hear it. May I start with a general question? I will leave it to you to decide who answers it. I should add that this is a first for this Committee in the Parliament. We have not previously invited colleagues to give evidence on the record.  Could you start by telling us what you hoped to achieve with the visit?
default              
defaultMr Straw:default I will ask my colleagues to come in on this. What I hoped to achieve was a loosening of relations, or a warming up of relations with 
defaultIran
default after a period when they had been in cold storage. As colleagues will know, I have taken a long-standing interest in 
defaultIran
default going back to the first few months when I was Foreign Secretary, and I visited it five times when I was Foreign Secretary. I did my best, with my colleagues, initially Dominique de 
defaultVillepin
default and 
defaultJoschka
default Fischer, to achieve agreement with the Iranians on the nuclear dossier. We got quite close to it, but were frustrated in what we could achieve because of resistance by essentially the 
defaultneocons
default in the Bush Administration. I kept warning them that that would lead to a situation where the 
defaultKhatami
default Administration were undermined to the point where they would lose office, and indeed that happened, and they begat the 
defaultAhmadinejad
default regime for eight years. 
default              
defaultWith the election of President 
defaultRouhani
default in June last year, and his assumption of office in early August, we all thought that there was an opportunity. There were quite long negotiations about going to 
defaultTehran
default, but they came off and we went there in early January.
default              
defaultLord Lamont:default May I first draw attention to my entry in the Register of Members’ Financial Interests? I am the unpaid chairman of the British Chamber of Commerce and I have been involved with a company that has had an interest in 
defaultIran
default, although it does not do any trading with it.
default              
defaultI do not think I have much to add to what Mr Straw has said. I saw it as a natural follow-on to the fact that the 
defaultGeneva
default negotiations had begun and the fact that 
defaultBritain
default is exploring better relations and reopening the embassy. It seemed natural. I have had an interest in 
defaultIran
default for a decade of so.
default              
defaultMr Wallace:default I was the last British MP to visit in 2008, and I wanted to go and see what had changed, and I think there were four things. I wanted to know whether there was a real attempt, behind the words, to resolve the issues with the 5+1 and the greater issues. I wanted to get a sense of how strong the President was in his own position to be able to deliver, because it is not just about whether they can make a deal, but whether a deal can be delivered. I wanted to see whether there was any opposition, because it is quite a pluralistic society. Finally, we went to look at the embassy to see whether there was a pressing need for the reopening of diplomatic ties at a practical level as well as at a policy level. 
default              
defaultJeremy defaultCorbyndefault:default It was an extremely interesting visit. My view was that it was important to engage with 
defaultIran
default, to hope that there will be a reopening of full diplomatic relations with 
defaultIran
default and hope that nuclear talks will succeed to a good conclusion within six months and that the sanctions will ultimately be lifted. I also wanted the opportunity to engage with 
defaultIran
default because of the great deal of history between this country and 
defaultIran
default, most of it not very good, but also to raise issues of human rights and the 
defaultdiaspora
default—there are a very large number of Iranian people living in 
defaultBritain
default. Although it was a short visit, we were able to engage to a considerable extent mainly with the political classes in 
defaultTehran
default. However, I think we have helped to open the way for future visits and future delegations, and hopefully an inward delegation from 
defaultIran
default to this country, so that we build a constructive dialogue that can engage with all of those issues. 
