default              
defaultQ86default 
defaultSir Menzies Campbell:default May I ask you a question about the perceptions of your visit? A visit of this kind, particularly when it attracts such publicity, as it inevitably would because of the history, often has an effect on perception. One organisation described your visit as a disgraceful act of appeasement. Is that a perception that you have seen or heard more widely expressed? 
default              
defaultMr Straw:default That one organisation was the 
defaultNational Council of Resistance of Iran
default, which, as 
defaultMandy Rice-Davies
default famously opined, would say that, wouldn’t they? Let us be clear about the NCRI: they are a front organisation for the People’
defaults 
defaultMojahedin
default of Iran
default—the MEK—which I, as Home Secretary, banned at the request of the British Foreign Office as a terrorist organisation in the first list of proscribed organisations. That was lifted, as a result of legal action by the MEK, in 2009 across the EU, but I think there is overwhelming evidence that the decision I took was justified. Across the piece in 
defaultIran
default, you will find people spitting tacks about the MEK, because of the numbers of people who were killed by MEK terrorism and the fact that it joined with the Iraqis in the Iran-Iraq war and unquestionably it was 
defaultIran
default that was the victim of that military action.
default              
defaultAs for other reaction, I can give you an English language summary of the coverage in 
defaultIran
default—
defaultSir Menzies Campbell:default I 
defaultwas
default 
defaultgoing
default to come on to that.
default              
defaultMr Straw:default The visit got a lot of attention in 
defaultIran
