defaultQ118 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default Our next witness is Mr Mark Fitzpatrick, who is director of the non-proliferation and disarmament programme at the International Institute for Strategic Studies? May I welcome you, Mr Fitzpatrick, and apologise for the fact you had to wait? I hope you agree that we have just had a very interesting session. Is there something you would like to say by way of opening remarks?
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default Yes, Mr Chairman. I thought I would speak for a couple of minutes about my impressions of the joint plan of action that was being discussed towards the end of that previous session. I am positive for the short term. Under the joint plan of action, 
defaultIran
default’s nuclear capabilities are capped. The time to produce a weapons-worth of highly enriched uranium will double instead of being halved by next December as had been projected. The threat of war has been put off. 
defaultIran
default’s pragmatic new President delivered on his promise to start 
defaultdialling
default back sanctions, and his negotiators made most of the compromises. Neither side has any incentive to cheat.
default              
defaultThe wind has come out of the sails of the 
defaultUS
default Congressional push to adopt new sanctions, which would scuttle diplomacy in my view. There is growing recognition that to be politically viable, any final deal would have to allow some degree of enrichment on 
defaultIran
default’s soil. But I am pessimistic about the long term. The two sides are simply too far apart in their demands for what a comprehensive deal must entail. 
default              
defaultThe west wants deep cutbacks, elimination of the vast majority of the centrifuges and 
defaultFordow
default and 
defaultArak
default facilities and for the period of limitations to last up to 20 years. It also wants clarity concerning the evidence of 
defaultIran
default’s past weapons development work. 
defaultIran
default does not want to dismantle anything or to give up its capability to be able to produce nuclear weapons. It is willing to make tactical adjustments, but it seeks limits that last only a short time. In exchange, 
defaultIran
default wants all sanctions lifted.
default              
defaultThere are technical solutions, as Lord Lamont mentioned. Rather than being 
defaultdumbed
default down, 
defaultArak
default can be upgraded to a light-water reactor with conditions that make it proliferation-resistant. The time frame for the limitations can be left up to the IAEA to apply neutral objective criteria. If 
defaultIran
default accepts and fully implements the additional protocol, after a few years the IAEA could draw up conclusions about no undeclared nuclear activity.
default              
defaultWhether the solutions are politically acceptable to the key capitals, however, I doubt. My best guess is that the negotiators will not produce a comprehensive agreement and that at the end of the six months the interim period will be rolled over, probably with some further incremental limits to both the nuclear programme and to sanctions. Whether it can be rolled over for more than another six months is too early to tell, especially in the light of the mid-term US elections in November.
defaultQ119 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default Thank you very much indeed, Mr Fitzpatrick. I know you were listening to the last session and heard the members of the all-party group. Do you agree with their assessment right at the end that if Mr 
defaultAhmadinejad
default was still the President there would have been no agreement and no joint plan of action?
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default I think that is a fair assessment. He could not have still been President because the term of election was eight years, but Mr 
defaultJalili
default, who was presumed to be the front-runner, supported by the Supreme Leader, would not, I think, have made this deal.
defaultQ120 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default Who is in charge of the nuclear programme now?
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default That is a tough question. There is a kind of consensus way that decisions are made in 
defaultIran
default. Ultimately, of course, the Supreme Leader has the say and nothing will happen of this importance without his agreement, but he alone cannot make a decision that is contrary to the views of the others in what is sometimes called the elite. So there are various circles of power and a kind of consensus.
default              
defaultWho is in charge of the nuclear programme? On the one hand it is the Atomic Energy Organisation of Iran, led by an ally of the President, but I do not think that they are in charge of the 
defaultweaponisation
default work of which there has been evidence in the past. I think military organisations are in charge of that which run—or have run—parallel operations. 
defaultQ121 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default Do you buy the argument that there are factions in 
defaultIran
default who will actively try to prevent a deal from being done?
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default I am certain that there are opponents to this deal and they probably could be described as factions. Parts of the Iranian Revolutionary Guard Corps are doing very well under the current sanctions regime: they reap the black market profits from the sanctions when private businesses cannot compete. I think, just for pure commercial reasons, they might oppose the deal, but they might also oppose it because they do not like the west—the United Kingdom and the United States—and they do not want to do business with us. 
defaultQ122 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default Last year, you told us that 
defaultIran
default was capable of producing enough fissile material to make a nuclear bomb within months. Is that still your assessment?
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default Yes, but, as I mentioned in my opening statement, that time period will probably double under the joint plan of action, because the 20% enriched uranium will be eliminated. That makes it take longer to produce the fissile material. 
defaultQ123 default&#xa0; 
defaultMr Baron:default Not so long ago, and staying with Iran’s capacity to produce a nuclear bomb, opinion was cleanly divided between those who thought that Iran had made the decision and was in the process of taking on a nuclear weapons programme, with it being a question of time, and others who believed that they were just trying to get to the point of capability without having made the decision to take the next step. What is your assessment?
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default My assessment is that 
defaultIran
default has had a nuclear weapons capability for some time. It is not one point; it is a continuum, and they have wanted to be able to produce a nuclear weapon in a short amount of time if they make the political decision to do so. I have seen no evidence that they have made that decision. So I would say that they wanted to get that capability better and better so they would have it if circumstances were to mean that they wanted to go the rest of the way.
defaultQ124 default&#xa0; 
defaultMr Baron:default What is your answer to those, including the western powers, who looked at the last IAEA report—going back to November 2011—and concluded from that that Iran had definitely made a decision to go for it, despite there being no smoking gun?
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default I am not aware of too many analysts who were so certain that 
defaultIran
default had made a decision to produce nuclear weapons. Most of the analysts I respect voiced opinions similar to the one I did: that they wanted to get to the point where they could make a dash for it, if they made a decision to do so.
defaultQ125 default&#xa0; 
defaultSir Menzies Campbell:default Who would you say made the running and can claim the credit for the plan for the discussions that led to the joint plan of action? Where did the impetus come from?
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default I think that there are probably multiple impetuses, but I would say that the sanctions were certainly part of it. They created a political environment that helped 
defaultRouhani
default win the election. In the election debate, the nuclear issue came up, as did the sanctions. If you take a poll in 
defaultIran
default, you will find, as some pollsters have, that most people do not say that they voted for 
defaultRouhani
default because he wanted to get rid of sanctions. They ascribe other reasons, but sanctions certainly were part of it and his desire to turn a corner was another part of it. He was interested in a pragmatic way of moving forward. He wanted to be able to retain the capability, but to be willing to make tactical adjustments that would allow sanctions to be lifted.
defaultQ126 default&#xa0; 
defaultSir Menzies Campbell:default And on the other side of the argument?
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default Certainly the six powers are all led by Governments that wanted to make a deal, and obviously they have.
defaultQ127 default&#xa0; 
defaultSir Menzies Campbell:default I am just interested in what the dynamic was. How was it that something which had seemed impossible until 
defaultRouhani’s
default election—
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default I think that one could make a distinction with a year and a half ago, when the negotiations were going on in a series of capitals—
defaultBaghdad
default, 
defaultIstanbul
default and 
defaultMoscow
default. In each of those capitals the six powers came with a proposal and 
defaultIran
default did not want to negotiate. They offered a completely unrealistic set of demands. They weren’t really negotiations. 
defaultIran
default changed its President and he was willing actually to negotiate, to be transactional. That is the biggest factor.
defaultQ128 default&#xa0; 
defaultMike Gapes:default May I take you to the joint plan of action? What are the main concessions that the western side has made to get this agreement and—the same question I asked the parliamentarians—can you see any obvious loopholes or problems?
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default The west started off with some demands. Remember the three famous demands: stop, ship and shut. Stop the 20% enrichment, ship out the accumulated stockpile of 20% and shut down 
defaultFordow
default. They got “stop”, they didn’t get “ship” or “shut”, so you might say that they made concessions in their demands. They didn’t get everything that they asked for, nor did they get the amount of clarity about the past work at places like 
defaultParchin
default. They made concessions on sanctions, but I would argue that what they gave up is rather minuscule in contrast to the amount of sanctions that 
defaultIran
default remains under.
default              
defaultThe loopholes that I worry about a little bit are that 
defaultIran
default is allowed to maintain R and D on advanced centrifuges. They are allowed to keep some of the second, third and fourth generation—even sixth generation—centrifuges spinning at the pilot plant at 
defaultNatanz
default, and they will be doing development work somewhere else.
defaultQ129 default&#xa0; 
defaultMike Gapes:default May I ask you about this question of concealment of sites? The 
defaultFordow
default facility was not acknowledged, it was discovered late, in 2009. Could we make an assumption that there might be other secret sites that we do not know about that might yet be disclosed or detected, and blow apart the whole deal?
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default I think it is a pretty fair assumption that there are some other facilities that have not been revealed, because it is 
defaultIran
default’s policy not to reveal nuclear facilities until such a time as they are about ready to come into operation. That is their policy, so, yes, I think 
defaultthere
default very well could be other facilities. Now, would the discovery of those facilities lead to the deal being blown up? Quite possibly, depending on how far along they were. If they had centrifuges running in violation of IAEA safeguards requirements—they have to declare before any centrifuges actually run with uranium in them—then that, I think, would blow it up. If there were empty halls, maybe it wouldn’t blow up the deal, but it would certainly create some trouble.
defaultQ130 default&#xa0; 
defaultMike Gapes:default May I also ask you about 
defaultParchin
default? Perhaps you could clarify, because we got into an exchange earlier. Is the omission of mention of 
defaultParchin
default in the joint action plan a serious problem?
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default I don’t think it is a serious problem, because the E3+3 negotiations with 
defaultIran
default were focused on their current actions and activities and the future, as Mr Wallace said. There is a separate diplomatic forum to talk about the issues of the past. Those are the 
defaultdiplomatic discussions going on with the IAEA. You are certainly right: the IAEA has asked repeatedly to go to 
defaultParchin
default and the IAEA’s new deal, which they got with 
defaultIran
default recently, does not allow 
defaultParchin
default. I do not think even that is a show-stopper, because I don’t think the IAEA is going to find anything at 
defaultParchin
default even if they went.
default              
defaultMike Gapes:default Because they took all the earth away.
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default Yes, and they cleaned it out and so forth. So I wouldn’t make such a big deal about it. The main point is this: 
defaultIran
default has to explain these allegations of past 
defaultweaponisation
default work. They have to be able to explain why there is so much evidence of that, even if it is not conclusive. Until they do, the IAEA won’t be able to fully come to grips with their programme.
defaultI don’t think that you could just sweep that under the rug and say: “Well, the past is past, they did 
defaultweaponisation
default work in the past” and forget about it. You have to have a starting place to be able to evaluate future activities and whether that was really all in the past or whether it is present.
defaultQ131 default&#xa0; 
defaultMike Gapes:default Another question that comes out of the joint plan of action is this agreement that they were going to dilute the uranium oxide back to a form which can be used in centrifuges. How long does that take and how easy is it to do? Can it be done secretly?
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default Perhaps I could just rephrase your question. The issue is one of reconversion of the oxide to the 
defaultgasified
default form. How long does that take, could it be done in secret? There is debate about how long it can take. Most technical experts who understand how centrifuge and uranium enrichment work will tell you it doesn’t take too long at all, maybe a few weeks once you have a line established to do it. Setting up the line might take a few weeks and then actually doing it might only take a couple of weeks. Could it be done in secret? The activity could probably be done in secret, but probably not, because the material itself is safeguarded. The IAEA keeps watch on that oxide, so if it is taken away somewhere and done in a secret facility, the IAEA would discover that.
defaultQ132 default&#xa0; 
defaultMdefaultike Gapes:default Finally, the joint action plan establishes a joint commission which is supposed to work with the IAEA to facilitate resolution of past and present issues of concern. You have alluded to some of these issues in the past; how will this joint commission work and what will it be dealing with?
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default I won’t be able to answer that question very well because that is one of the details that is not spelled out in what has been made public by the implementation plan. They just announced that there is going to be this body. It is pretty common in these kinds of negotiations to have 
defaultsome body
default, but I don’t have any insights into how exactly it will work.
defaultQ133 default&#xa0; 
defaultMike Gapes:default Is it possible that there will be a separate, secret agreement about how it will work?
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default I wouldn’t call it a secret agreement exactly. It is established diplomatic process that when you have detailed negotiations such as this, some parts are not made public. It is actually an indication of the seriousness of the negotiators that they don’t run out and make everything public. I know that in my country, the 
defaultUnited States
default, some legislators are demanding that it be made public because they fear that there might be some secret thing 
defaultthat could be to the detriment of their country, but as a former diplomat I do not think it is too unusual.
defaultQ134 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default Do you accept that it might be possible to agree with the IAEA and not agree with the requirements of the joint plan of action?
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default This may not answer your question exactly—
default              
defaultChair:default You may rephrase my question if you want. I rather like that phrase.
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default Thank you—you are being very generous. I think there is an issue here that you are both touching on, that these two sets of diplomatic negotiations are not addressing the same set of issues and they could come into conflict, because the IAEA’s role is to clarify past activity, while the six powers are looking to the future and some of them might seek to forget about what happened in the past. I saw this happen in the 
defaultNorth Korea
default negotiations. We never got to the bottom of what happened with North Korea’s past nuclear activity and the IAEA was excluded from being able to verify this when the US-North Korea agreement came into place. It only verified the new agreement, not the past. I hope that that does not happen with the 
defaultIran
default case.
defaultQ135 default&#xa0; 
defaultMike Gapes:default It is not a good precedent, is it?
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default No.
defaultQ136 default&#xa0; 
defaultSir John Stanley:default Do you think that Iran may have a concealed plutonium route to a nuclear weapons programme other than possibly at Arak?
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default I don’t think it would be so easy to conceal a plutonium route fully because you have first to produce the plutonium in a reactor, and reactors give off signals of heat and they’re large. The better question might be, might they have a secret reprocessing facility so that they could take the spent fuel that comes out of 
defaultArak
default and make it weapons-usable? It is not so hard to have a secret reprocessing facility, but the IAEA will be safeguarding the spent fuel, so if it is diverted, the inspectors would know about that. 
defaultQ137 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default Are you confident that 
defaultIran
default will stick to the terms of the deal? 
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default I think 
defaultIran
default has every incentive to stick to the terms of the deal, because they want these sanctions lifted. If they break the deal, not only would they lose the small benefits that they are getting, they would lose the hope of future benefits, and the sanctions would pile on. The United States Senate has additional sanctions on the shelf. If 
defaultIran
default breaks the deal, even the Obama Administration would be in favour of imposing new sanctions.
default              
defaultThe issue might be, though, would 
defaultIran
default do something in some other realm, such as secret facilities, that would scuttle the deal. They would not intend to do it, but they would do something that would have an external impact. It might not be secret nuclear facilities: it could be something in 
defaultSyria
default. Say the Iranian Revolutionary Guards, who are already assisting the Assad regime, assisted in a bigger way with more troops—right now, they are mostly putting in advisers. That could cause a backlash in western capitals.
default              
defaultQ138 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default They have to come back to the table within one year. Some people have said that actually all they want is six-month deals that just keep rolling over. Do you think there is any merit in that?
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default I do not think that 
defaultIran
default is the party that is most interested in rolling over the deal in order to, as is often said, buy time while they continue some nuclear work. They have already been continuing all their nuclear work with no negotiations, so having negotiations doesn’t give them any additional benefit: in fact, it caps their programme. They are probably the ones who are more in a hurry to get a final deal, even though they do not talk that way. They talk as though it is, “Oh well, maybe let the West be the ones”, but they have an incentive. The West probably has an incentive to keep it capped. If there is not a comprehensive deal struck in the next six months, it is probably to western capitals’ benefit to roll this over to keep the lid on the programme.
defaultQ139 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default From what you were saying a moment ago, you seemed to acknowledge that the sanctions are working—they have had an impact—in negotiating terms. 
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default Yes, that is my belief. The sanctions had an impact in persuading 
defaultIran
default to come to the table and to try to strike a deal quickly.
defaultQ140 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default So it was a combination of 
defaultRouhani’s
default election and sanctions?
default 
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default defaultThat is my answer, yes.
defaultQ141 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default Can you see any viable alternatives to the joint plan of action?
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default No, I think the alternative to the joint plan of action is a no-deal and 
defaultIran
default shortening this period by which it could have a weapon and moving to a path toward war. The alternative of no-deal is a very scary path.
defaultQ142 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default So you think we will do a deal, do you?
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default I am certainly in favour of it, yes.
defaultChair:default But do you think it will happen? Do you think a long-term comprehensive agreement will be reached?
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default No, I don’t. I think it would be too difficult politically for 
defaultIran
default to accept the limits that would be required and for 
defaultWashington
default to give 
defaultIran
default what it wants in terms of lifting sanctions. I was asked earlier what percentage I would assign to a comprehensive deal, and I said 10%. Then I was asked what percentage for another six-month deal, a roll-over. I said 80%. That leaves 10% for a total collapse and a calamity.
defaultQ143 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default You said in answer to a question from Mr Gapes a moment ago that it was possible that there were hidden facilities. That, coupled with the fact that you give an 80% improbability of a comprehensive agreement being reached, is a fairly pessimistic picture. 
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default These hidden facilities that are probably out there somewhere may not have too much equipment in them, and that alone would not scuttle the deal.
defaultQ144 default&#xa0; 
defaultChair:default On that cheery note, I have to confess that you have been a Chairman’s dream. We have actually got the programme back on track today and you have answered all our questions succinctly and accurately. For that I thank you very much.
default              
defaultMark Fitzpatrick:default You are welcome. Thank you for having me again. 
default              
defaultChair:default 
defaultThank
default you. 
